"Mark Twain, in an article printed several years ago, spoke of a plan that he had frequently practiced, i.e., that of writing a letter to a person upon some subject, then addressing the envelope and inserting the letter, and then tearing the whole thing into pieces instead of sending it.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"He stated that in a large percentage of such cases he would receive within a short time a letter from the person to whom the destroyed letter had been addressed, answering the questions asked, or else speaking along the same lines as those of the destroyed letter.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"We have known of this experiment being tried on people thousands of miles away from the writer, and also in cases in which the other person had not been heard of for many years.",0,0,0,0,0,0
