GENERAL REMARKS ON PRACTICE.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The above exercises will train the student to receive and act upon the mental commands or messages of the Transmitter, under a great variety of circumstances and conditions.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Many of the most successful public Mind Readers started out in public work with far less careful and thorough training.,0,0,0,0,0,0
But there are now still greater degrees of proficiency possible.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The student will find in succeeding chapters a number of interesting and startling feats and experiments which are intended for parlor audiences, etc., but which may be most profitably practiced previously with the aid of a good friendly Transmitter, in order that the Performer may familiarize himself with the details of the experiment, and thus be more at his ease when he demonstrates it in public.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Then other new experiments and feats will suggest themselves from time to time, to the intelligent student which, likewise, should be practiced previous to a public demonstration.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"In finding a hidden object, the first thing to do is to get an idea of the direction.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Then the general location of the hiding place; and so on, from general impressions to detailed ones, until at last the fingers close upon the object itself.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"The Transmitter will be greatly relieved when the object is finally found, and the relaxing of his mental tension may be distinctly felt, and then you will know that your search is at an end.",1,0,0,0,0,0
PREPARING FOR PUBLIC WORK.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Before taking you on with the work before an audience, we must urge upon you to prepare yourself thoroughly by means of the above mentioned exercises.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"The great tendency among students is to hurry through to the public work, and skipping the exercises as much as possible.",0,0,0,0,0,0
This is all wrong.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"You will never be a thoroughly good demonstrator of anything in life, until you master the rudiments, and by practice familiarize yourself thoroughly with the details of the work.",0,0,0,0,0,0
And Mind Reading is no exception.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It is true that after a few exercises you may be able to give a fair demonstration before an audience, but you will never get further than fair without careful practice.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"And therefore we urge you to have patience and perseverance, and to stick to the exercise until you become a Master of Mind Reading, when you need fear no audience whatsoever, and will be able to give a demonstration that will be a great credit to both yourself and to us, your instructors.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"And, now for your work before an audience, remembering, always that the feats and experiments that we shall mention, should be practiced by you privately, with the aid of a friendly Transmitter, before you reproduce them in public.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"In the case of feats, in which the audience is a party to the experiment, such as the finding of a scarf-pin on a member of the audience, you may practice with a dummy audience, that is with an imaginary audience consisting of chairs, etc., until you familiarize yourself with the details of the feat.",1,0,0,0,0,0
LESSON V. SIMPLE DEMONSTRATIONS.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"In beginning a public demonstration, it will be well for you to give a short preliminary talk to the audience, somewhat along the following lines: OPENING TALK.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Ladies and Gentlemen, with your assistance I shall endeavor to give you a demonstration of practical Mind Reading, beginning with some simple feats, and then proceeding gradually to more complicated demonstrations.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"In these demonstrations, I must have your co-operation, for the success of the experiments depends as much upon you as upon myself.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"In the first place, I must ask that you refrain from conversation, laughter, etc., while I am demonstrating, for these things distract the mind of the Transmitter and prevent him from concentrating his Mind and Will upon mine; and also prevent me from maintaining that Passive Mental State which is essential to the success of the experiments.",1,1,1,1,1,1
I trust that you will help me in this way.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"I also ask that during the experiments, you will all concentrate your Mind and Will upon me, and help me in the work.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"In order to obtain the best results all Mind Readers prefer that their audiences concentrate their Wills upon the work, with the purpose of mentally willing that the demonstrator be successful.",1,0,0,0,0,0
In fact the success of the experiments depend very materially upon the _Willing_ exerted by the audience.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"If you Will in my favor, I shall be successful; if you Will that I shall fail, I shall feel the effect.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Therefore, kindly give me your aid.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"I ask you to blindfold me and take such other means to prevent unfair methods and practices, as your judgment may dictate.",1,0,0,0,0,0
I am now ready to proceed with the tests.,0,0,0,0,0,0
